#
KILL HIT

Syntax:  hit [monster] [location]

A good way to start a fight.  After the name of the monster that you
want to kill, you have the option to aim for a certain location of
the body.  Possible locations are feet, legs, arms, body, and head.
Aiming is useful when you want to attack a monster in a certain
place.  For example, a warrior might have heavily armored arms
and legs, but not much in the body.  In that case, 'hit warrior body'
would be a good choice.  For more information, see HELP LOCATIONS.
#
LOCATIONS

The five primary hit locations are: feet, legs, body, arms, head.
For monsters whose anatomy doesn't quite match up to a humanoid's,
the locations are substituded with more realistic ones.  For
example, a dragon might have locatios claws, legs, body, wings, head
or a spider might have feet, legs, body, legs, head.

When you attack a certain location, whether or not you hit depends
on the relative height differences and how well the location is
armored.  A giant would have an easy time hitting a gnome's head,
but the gnome would have a bit of difficulty hitting the giant's!

Hitting a certain location also has the potention of doing more
or less damage.  For example, hit a hit to the arm scores only
80% of the damage a hit to the body would.

Consider all of this when initiating combat.

CrossReference:  See HELP COMBAT
#
COMBAT

There are several things to remember in order to be successful in
combat.   The first is that you can attack a monster in five different
location: the feet, legs, arms, body and head.  Certain locations are
armoured differently, so those might be good places to strike.  Also,
hitting a limb does a bit less damage then hitting the head or body.
Plus, some armor now absorbs melee damage...thus reducing the amount
of hitpoints both you and the mob will take.  Consider all of this
when attacking.  For example.

Lashi considers killing a dragon.  He could attack in the body, head,
or a limb.  Lashi figures that the wings are fragile and are less
armoured than the body, thus he could hit the dragon more often there.
He also considers that a hit to the wing won't do as much damage as
a hit to the body.  Finally, he decides that, since the wing has less
stopping power, he could actually do more damage to the wing than
to the body.  Of course, this is all moot, because Lashi is a pixie
and has no chance of hitting a dragon's wings (he's too small) :)

#
KICK

The success of a kick depends upon how well you are learned. The
higher level you reach the harder you kick. There is one small catch -
whenever you kick (or miss) you will be unable to type any command for
three rounds of 'Violence' - so be sure that you do not need to flee!

Fighters See Also : Rescue, Bash
#
BASH

  The success of a bash depends upon how well you are learned. To bash
someone is to attempt to 'knock' that person over. If you succeed you
will inflict minor damage, and cause the victim to fall on its rear.
The victim will be unable to issue any commands for 2 rounds of
violence. If you miss you loose your balance and fall.
  A bash makes you unable to type commands for 2 rounds of violence.
Note that hitting a person who is resting/sitting will inflict
1.5*damage.  Fighters See Also : Rescue, Kick
#
RESCUE

  A rescue is an attempt to make a monster hit you instead of the
person being rescued. You can only 'turn' one monster for each
attempt. This is highly useful when playing in groups.
#
STEAL

Use steal to steal gold or items from people. The chance of not
getting caught depends on how well you have practiced steal, and if
the person is asleep.

Example:

  > steal gold drunk

#
BACKSTAB

Is a way to sneak up on a person, and attempt to place you dagger in
his bag, at exactly the point where it does most damage. A successful
backstab gives a damage multiplier, depending on level:

The chance of successfully backstabbing a person depends on how well
you have practiced backstab at your guild.

If you are an assassin, see HELP ASSASSINATE for more information.
#
CAST
For "magical" people. If you want to throw a spell at someone or something.
Example : cast 'burning hands' <player>
   Note that the name of the spell must be enclosed by "'"s.

See also : help on each individual spell, for example:
  > help cure ligh
  > help ventri
  > help energy drain
#
DROP
If you lose interest in a carried item, you can drop it on the ground.
Example : drop bottle
  If you feel like getting rid of all your earthly possessions, you
may use "drop all".  Also you can drop 9*bottle, which would drop 9
bottles, but leave the rest in your hands.
  You can also type drop all*bottle to drop all of the bottles you have.

See also: GET
#
PURGE
A way to make the world a little cleaner.
Usage:
  purge                         To empty a room of monsters and objects.
  purge <character>             To remove a living thing. Kicks out a player.
  purge <object>                Figure this one out yourself.
  purge room                    imp only

#
PSTAT
  If you are interested in a person and want to find out about
his/her/its skills, strength, mana, hitpoints etc. In addition, 'stat
room' will give you useful information about the room you are in.

#
MSTAT

     Shows you the stats of a given mob.
#
RSTAT

     This command will display almost everything you need to know about
a room (it only works for the room you are in, unless you use  mat or
at).  It will display the sector type, room flags, all exits along with
their flags and any exdscs, all characters currently in the room, and all
objects in the room.
#
STAT

     Stat <object>  will show you all of the characteristics of a given
object.  The ONLY reason to do this is if you are looking at examples while
making your own objects, or if a player thinks their equipment is bugged.
In other words, DON'T STAT OBJECTS FOR MORTALS!!  :)
#
NOHASSLE

     This command toggles your nohassle setting (immortals only).  If you
turn on nohassle, aggressive mobs will not attack you.  To turn it back
off, just enter  nohassle  again.  Be SURE to turn on nohassle if you are
going to be near aggressive mobs in the mortal areas.  It is Bad Form to
end up hurting a mob because you forge to set nohassle and it attacked
you.
