OCREATE

Syntax:
  ocreate new #
  ocreate old #
  ocreate one Name *** 2009+ only

 ocreate new #    will load into your workspace a blank object with the
                  given virtual #

 ocreate old #    will load into your workspace a copy of the object # that
                  you previously saved with osave

 ocreate one Name will search the world for an object with the given
                 Name.  Changes that you make on this will instantly be
                  reflected on the object, even if it is in use.
                  You do not need to use osave with this.

If you use ocreate and you have not previously saved your workspace with
osave, your workspace will be cleared.  So if you mess up on an object,
and want to start from scratch, just just ocreate new # again.  If you
oload an object right after ocreating it, and don't osave first, you will
get one copy of the object BUT will not be able to save it afterwards.

NOTES:
    1) Player bits do not and will not work, so don't bother using them.
    2) If you want a certain item to have stats beyond what ocreate will
         allow you to use, you must ask an Imp to fix it for you (you'll
         have to have a pretty good reason, too).

See Also: OLOOK, OSAVE, OCREATE, SPELL-INFO, SPELL-INFO2 ITEM_??? (where ???
is something like boat, light, weapon, food etc of object types)
#
OSAVE
Syntax:
  osave

  osave will save a copy of your workspace to disk.  If anything is already
  there, it will be overwritten.
#
OLOOK
Syntax:
  olook

  olook will show you a copy of your workspace.  It has almost the same
  format as stat.
#
OEDIT

Syntax:
  oedit field value [value]


Note: if you use oedit without parameters, it will list the legal fields.

Currently, the legal fields are:
  value1 - value4 : Each item uses different sets of these  (See OVALUE)
  type:  What type of item is it                            (See OTYPE)
  wear:  Where this can be worn                             (See OWEAR)
  xflag: If it hums, glows, etc                             (See OXFLAG)
  weight: how much the object weighs
  cost:  How much this object is worth if sold
  rent:  How much it costs to rent this object
  timer: Only affects objects already in the game
  bits:  Which player bits to set                           (See OBITS)
  aff1 - aff5: Which affects this has                       (See OAFFECTS)
                This requires two paramters, the first is what it affects,
                the second, by how much.
  name: The names the object can be called "black dagger blade"
        USE: oedit name black dagger blade
  short: The string used in most cases 'Blarg gets "short" from
bag.'
        USE: oedit short The short Sword
  long: What is seen when an object is sitting in a room "A blade is here."
        USE: oedit long <return>
             blah blah blah blah <return>
             @ <return>
  action: DONT USE
  extra:
        These are the extra descriptions.  Here is how you would use it:
        oedit extra handle
        ] The handle is made of fine silver.
        ] @
        oedit extra silver
        ] Its nice and shiny.
        ] There is an engraving.
        ] @

See Also: OLOOK, OSAVE, OCREATE, SPELL-INFO, SPELL-INFO2

#
ITEM_LIGHT

ITEM_LIGHT (1)
Value[0]: Not Used
Value[1]: Not Used
Value[2]: Number of hours the light can be used for. Zero hours means that
          the light has gone out. A negative number will create an eternal
          light source.
Value[3]: Not Used
#
ITEM_SCROLL

ITEM_SCROLL (2)
Value[0]: Level of the spell on the scroll.
Value[1]: Which spell (see list somewhere around the end of file)
Value[2]: Which spell
Value[3]: Which spell
  The values(1-3) are three (or less) different spells, mixed 'on' the scroll.
  Unused spells should be set to -1.
#
ITEM_WAND

ITEM_WAND (3)
Value[0]: Level of spell in wand.
Value[1]: Max Charges (1..X)
Value[2]: Charges Left
Value[3]: Which spell in wand (see list somewhere around the end of file)
#
